cp|8|AT|

^b@2^*BMarty Bergen: ^*N|cp||at|There is very little risk at the 1-level. That is not necessarily true against a major suit opening. Now your partner will frequently have to bid at the 2- level. If your partner is weak and your hand is nothing special, this can be a problem.|MB|x|NT||SK|e|lb|*bWhat do you bid with East hand?^^2h|cp|8|AT|
^b@2^*BMarty Bergen: ^*N|cp||at|East jumps to 2@H which is a weak jump shift. This is an important tool to be used in competitive auctions by the responder, regardless of whether the opponent has made a takeout double or an overcall.|mb|2h|
PG| ***** 7 ***** |


NT||cp|8|AT|
^b@2^*BMarty Bergen: ^*N|cp||at|East is showing a weak hand with a 6-card heart suit or possibly even a 7-card suit. The suit does not need to be strong. But you would like to have a suit where you don't have a big problem if partner has a singleton. |
PG| ***** 8 ***** |


NT||cp|8|AT|
^b@2^*BMarty Bergen: ^*N|cp||at|The requirements for making a 3-level weak jump shift are obviously stronger, not in terms of high card points, but the suit should be pretty good. Often the suit is 7-cards in length, particularly when vulnerable.|
PG| ***** 9 ***** |


